description.plain:
Jonathan Lyndale Kirk (b. December 22, 1991), better known as his stage name DaBaby (formerly Baby Jesus), is a rapper hailing from Charlotte, North Carolina.

His 2018 songs “Next Song” and “Blank Blank” have received cosigns from the likes of Boosie Badazz and Yo Gotti, but his true ascent began when he dropped the music video to his viral hit “Walker Texas Ranger” on the first day of 2019.

In November 2018, DaBaby shot and killed a man attempting to rob him in a Walmart, which propelled his name up to new heights following various news reports on the incident. The murder charge was later dropped.

On March 1, 2019, DaBaby released his major-label debut studio album, Baby on Baby, after being signed to Interscope Records. It features collaborations from and the likes of Offset from the hip-hop trio Migos, Rich Homie Quan, Stunna 4 Vegas, and Rich the Kid.

On September 27, 2019, he released his second studio album, KIRK. It features collaborations from and the likes of Kevin Gates, Chance the Rapper, Gucci Mane, YK Osiris, Nicki Minaj, Lil Baby, Moneybagg Yo, Stunna 4 Vegas, and Migos. The album debuted at #1 on the Billboard 200, due to 145,000 album-equivalent units in its debut week.

On April 17, 2020, he released his third studio album BLAME IT ON BABY. It features collaborations from and the likes of Quavo from Migos, Future, jetsonmade, Roddy Ricch, YoungBoy Never Broke Again, A Boogie wit da Hoodie, London on da Track, Ashanti, and Megan Thee Stallion.

Outside of his own work, he has been featured on songs by many high-profile artists, including Dreamville, J. Cole and Lute, Megan Thee Stallion, Chance the Rapper, Camila Cabello, and Post Malone. He has also worked with artists on remixes of their popular songs, such as Lizzo, YG, Lil Nas X, Future, and Dua Lipa.

DaBaby also owns his own record label, Billion Dollar Baby Entertainment. Its current roster includes Stunna 4 Vegas, one of DaBaby’s most frequent collaborators; DJ K.i.D., DaBaby’s tour DJ and the producer behind most of BLAME IT ON BABY; and rising North Carolina artists Rich Dunk and 704chop.

In November of 2020, DaBaby released My Brother’s Keeper (Long Live G) after losing his older brother Glenn Johnson to suicide. The EP features artists Polo G, NoCap, Toosii, and Meek Mill.

songs.title: ROCKSTAR

description.plain:
Only seven months after likening himself to a “POP STAR,” DaBaby teams up with fellow 2019 superstar Roddy Ricch for “ROCKSTAR,” an ode to their reckless lifestyles.

DaBaby and Roddy draw hip-hop’s popular parallel between their life and that of rockstars, substituting a rocker’s typical guitar for a firearm. Additionally, the duo compares their rise to the top and express their loyalty to family and loved ones.

The song’s upbeat, guitar-driven trap instrumental is produced by DaBaby’s frequent collaborator, SethInTheKitchen, who notably produced Baby’s 2019 track, “iPHONE.”

songs.title: Suge

description.plain:
In the second track from his Baby on Baby album, Charlotte rapper DaBaby delivers a homage to Marion “Suge” Knight, the founder, and former head of Death Row Records.

Knight became the CEO of Death Row in 1991 when he was just 26 years old, which was just a year younger than DaBaby’s age at the time of this tracks release.

In the song, the rapper discusses several topics, including his riches, selling drugs, signing record deals, and threatening opposition.

“Suge” was officially released to radio as a single on April 23, 2019 and was certified Gold on May 15.

songs.title: INTRO

description.plain:
On the opening track to his sophomore album KIRK, North Carolina rapper DaBaby reminisces about his past and reflects on his rise to mainstream fame. In particular, DaBaby juxtaposes his poor upbringing with the newfound success he experiences, while also looking back on how he changed along the way.

This song was released in dedication of his deceased father and his grandmother, who untimely passed away during his come-up in the rap game. The “INTRO” is an unusual track from DaBaby, as it features hard-hitting lyricism and introspective bars, straying from his typical subject matter.

This track serves as the first promotional single for KIRK, which is unorthodox since rappers typically don’t release introduction tracks on albums as solo songs.

songs.title: Beatbox Freestyle

description.plain:
“Beatbox Freestyle” is DaBaby’s take on SpotEmGottem’s viral April 2020 single “Beat Box”—a song most known for its Pooh Shiesty-assisted remix “Beat Box 2”.

The freestyle was first teased with a one-minute snippet posted on DaBaby’s Instagram on 02/18/2021. The music video would be released a day after.

A week after the freestyle’s release–and its virality–SpotEmGottem made DaBaby’s freestyle an official remix of his song, titling it “Beat Box 3.”

description.plain:
This is the Black Lives Matter (BLM) remix to DaBaby’s April 2020 #1 hit single “ROCKSTAR” featuring Roddy Ricch. In his new verse, DaBaby addresses his multiple run-ins with the police, relating them to the nationwide George Floyd Protests in America on police brutality and systemic racism in the country.

DaBaby first teased this new verse to “ROCKSTAR” prior to its release on his Instagram story. Days later, the original song went #1 on the Billboard Hot 100.

The track’s instrumental is centered around a heavy bass line with a squeaky, electronic instrument providing the melody for the vocals of both rappers.

A music video was released for the track on the same day as its release, featuring similar quarantine themes to those seen on the album’s cover.

Straight off the rip, you know I dont wait for the drop

In addition, DaBaby keeps his flow hot by waiving the use of a chorus and, instead, uses one long verse to set the tone for his audience in the rest of KIRK.

To accompany the track’s popularity, Baby himself started a dance challenge, following a tweet on October 11, 2017, offering a cash prize for the best freestyle. This helped the track blow up even more then it already had. Videos of the challenge trended on Twitter and Instagram.

description.plain:
“Raw Shit” is a hard hitting trap anthem that reunites DaBaby with Offset, and features verses from the other two Migos members as well. On the braggadocios track, the artists team up to boast about their hardcore music and the way their fans enjoy their music.

During an interview with Charlie Sloth on August 1st, 2019, he revealed that he had features from all three Migos members on the track, which has become a rare occurrence due to their individual rap careers.

While this marks the first time that DaBaby has collaborated with all three Migos members, he did collaborate with Offset individually on March 2019’s “Baby Sitter.” and August 2019’s “Pink Toes.”

songs.title: Red Light Green Light

description.plain:
On “Red Light Green Light,” DaBaby raps about his usual topics of fast cars, cappin' rappers, and his sexual encounters.

The clarinet-based instrumental was produced by d.a. got that dope, who has previously worked with DaBaby on songs like “Masterpiece” and “BALL IF I WANT TO.” Fans were quick to point out the beat’s similarity to something played by Squidward, a popular character from SpongeBob SquarePants who plays the clarinet.

The song was released on June 25, 2021 alongside a music video, directed by DaBaby himself, which pays homage to one of rap’s favorite movies, 1991’s Boyz n the Hood.

songs.title: PEEP HOLE

description.plain:
“PEEP HOLE” is a powerful track from DaBaby, with him seeking to get past his old “player” lifestyle and move to a new phase in his life including a calmer way of life and more moments spent with his family. He also discusses his opinion on the current climate of America, especially the public tensions with law enforcement.

DaBaby first teased the track with a Triller video on July 30, 2020. He later previewed footage from the video shoot and confirmed the track’s title the day before its release. The song dropped alongside its music video on August 3.

This is the second single from the deluxe edition of BLAME IT ON BABY and was released a day before the revamped version.

songs.title: SHUT UP

description.plain:
DaBaby uses “SHUT UP” to address his haters and let everyone know that he hears and sees what people say. Yet, he only cares about his real fans and getting money. Much like some of his recent social media posts, he’s tired of people for speaking for him and taking what media outlets say too seriously.

The Reel Goats shot and edited music video is used to dive deeper into the ideas of not caring about his haters but only caring about his fans. Diddy and Kanye West are prominently featured in the music video and help DaBaby express how grateful he and his family are of his success.
